<subsection><title>Video summary</title>


<p>If we have a linear discrete dynamical system in 
<ref uri='doenet:function_iteration_form|page_type=definition'>function iteration form</ref>
, 
<mdn>
  <mrow>x_{t+1}\amp =R x_t
<!-- django tag equation_tag, function_iteration_form, , , , "1" -->

</mrow>
  <mrow>x_{0}\amp = \text{a known positive value},\notag</mrow>
</mdn>
then the 
<ref uri='doenet:doenetId=nzSdVA_gPhe5W-oM4IN5z'>solution is the exponential</ref>

<me>x_t = R^tx_0.</me>
Given that <m>x_0 \gt  0</m>, the solution will be positive as long as <m>R \gt  0</m>.  The value of <m>R</m> determines whether we get exponential growth or decay.</p>
<ul>
<li>If <m>R \gt  1</m>, then at each time step, the value of the state variable increases.  The solution exhibits exponential growth.  The growth makes sense because in each time step, we are multiplying by a number greater than 1.</li>
<li>If <m>0 \lt  R \lt 1</m>, then at each time step, the value of the state variable decreases.  The solution exhibits exponential decay.  The decay makes sense because in each time step, we are multiplying by a positive number less than 1.</li>
<li>If <m>R=1</m>, then the solution is a constant.  The constant solution makes sense because in each time step, we are multiplying by 1.</li>
</ul>

<p>On the other hand, if we have a linear dynamical system in 
<ref uri='doenet:difference_form|page_type=definition'>difference form</ref>
,
<mdn>
  <mrow>x_{t+1} - x_t\amp =r x_t
<!-- django tag equation_tag, difference_form, , , , "2" -->

</mrow>
  <mrow>x_{0}\amp = \text{a known positive value},\notag</mrow>
</mdn>
then, to  
<ref uri='doenet:doenetId=nzSdVA_gPhe5W-oM4IN5z'>solve the system</ref>
, we first must add <m>x_t</m> to both sides of the evolution rule, converting it into the equivalent system in function iteration form:
<md>
  <mrow>x_{t+1}\amp =(r +1)x_t</mrow>
  <mrow>x_{0}\amp = \text{a known positive value}.</mrow>
</md>
Its solution is the exponential
<me>x_t = (r+1)^tx_0.</me>
Given that <m>x_0 \gt  0</m>, the solution will be positive as long as <m>r \gt  -1</m>.  The value of <m>r</m> determines whether we get exponential growth or decay.</p>
<ul>
<li>If <m>r \gt  0</m>, then at each time step, the value of the state variable increases.  The solution exhibits exponential growth.  The growth makes sense because in each time step, we are adding a positive quantity.</li>
<li>If <m>-1 \lt  r \lt  0</m>, then at each time step, the value of the state variable decreases.  The solution exhibits exponential decay.  The decay makes sense because in each time step, we are subtracting a positive quantity, but we aren't subtracting off any more than the value of <m>x_t</m> in the previous time step.</li>
<li>If <m>r = 0</m>, then the solution is a constant.  The constant solution makes sense because in each time step, we are adding zero.</li>
</ul>







</subsection>

